{\rtlch\af2\alang1025\afs24\ltrch\b0\i0\fs20\lang1033\langnp1033\langfe1033\langfenp1033\loch\af2\dbch\af2\hich\f2\strike0\ulnone\cf3 Appellees, husband, wife, and children, brought a negligence and products liability action against appellant manufacturer for injuries resulting from appellee husband's use of a prescription sleeping pill. The trial court found appellant grossly negligent, awarded zero damages to appellee husband, awarded damages for loss of consortium to appellees, wife and children, but awarded no damages for loss-of-support. On appeal, the court reversed the judgment in favor of appellees. The court held that the award of loss of consortium and exemplary damages could not stand as a matter of law because appellee husband did not suffer any injuries from his use of the medication. The court affirmed the trial court's refusal to enter judgment on the jury's award for loss of support because loss of support damages were not recoverable in a personal injury action. The court also found that appellees' pleading put the continuing-tort rule in issue and that the trial court did not err when it denied appellant's motion for a directed verdict because appellant did not conclusively establish that the suit was brought more than two years after the limitations period commenced.}
